gretchen hofmann the leopold leadership program skip to main content search this site the leopold leadership program about fellows news fellowship information resources fellows login home 2013 fellowship information all cohort reunion june 19 21 2012 in this section fellows directory one of the best things i have ever done in my career it changed my views of how to do my job alan townsend 2001 gretchen hofmann gretchen hofmann contact information professor ecology evolution and marine biology university of california santa barbara gretchen hofmann is a marine biologist who studies the effects of climate change on marine animals specializing in marine invertebrates such as sea urchins and mussels her research has focused on how these organisms respond to the double jeopardy of ocean warming and ocean acidification her approach is to integrate many approaches from physiological to the genomics to assess how species will respond to changing environmental conditions in the world's oceans global change genomics has become a central part of her research program her research team of graduate students and postdocs at uc santa barbara have been using the purple sea urchin genome database to profile gene expression in response to conditions of ocean acidification in order ot develop genomic resources for other important calcifying organisms dr hofmann's group is using 454 pyrosequencing to obtain dna sequence for the pteropod limacina helicina a small pelagic snail that is a critical part of the food web in the southern ocean in addition to integrating tools of molecular biology to obtain high resolution data about the response of marine organisms to climate change dr hofmann's research is also directed at understanding which species will be vulnerable to climate change and is contributing to discussions about how vulnerable species might be identified in so that region by region solutions and plans can be made to prepare for unexpected changes that occur as a result of environmental change in the ocean in this area dr hofmann has contributed to the nature conservancy report on managing coral reefs in response to ocean acidification and talks about her research and how to think about climate change and ocean acidification with noaa channel island sanctuary dr hofmann serves on the us national science foundation's office of polar programs advisory committee and is a member of an nrc committee on the development of an integrated science strategy for ocean acidification monitoring research and impacts assessment tags north america oceans & coasts 2012 leopold leadership program the stanford woods institute for the environment stanford university stanford ca 94305
